<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  The cross-tabbed <strong>feature surface</strong> (capability × tool) over the workbench/docs-tool
  landscape from <a href="/backlog/624-inventory-the-component-workbench-docs-tool-landscape-storyb/">#624</a> —
  stage 2 of the Web Docs feature-pipeline epic
  (<a href="/backlog/623-web-docs-feature-pipeline-inventory-workbench-tools-derive-i/">#623</a>). It is the
  union of capabilities a Web-Everything-native docs surface must cover or consciously omit, and the raw
  material the derivation decision
  (<a href="/backlog/626-map-workbench-features-to-we-standards-which-intents-blocks-/">#626</a>) classifies.
</p>
<p>
  The machine-readable matrix lives in <code>src/_data/workbenchFeatures.json</code> (tool ids reference the
  <a href="/research/component-workbench-landscape/">workbench-tools registry</a>); this page renders from it.
  The load-bearing column is <strong>WE status</strong>: it pre-classifies each feature as reuse / extend an
  existing WE standard, genuinely new surface, or out-of-scope — so #626 is mostly a dedupe-and-compose
  exercise, not a greenfield mint.
</p>

<h2>The headline finding</h2>
<p>
  Roughly two thirds of the surface already maps to standards WE has. The genuinely-new core #626 must
  actually design is small: the <strong>component-isolation renderer</strong>, <strong>CEM-driven
  autodocs</strong> (the #624 emit prior — api-viewer is the zero-build proof), a <strong>search
  index</strong>, and a <strong>source/code view</strong>. Two features are out-of-scope for the standard
  layer (visual regression → a CI/hosted tier of the served product #398; the Figma design↔code bridge → a
  design-tool integration whose fully-hosted form, Backlight, already failed).
</p>

<h2>WE status legend</h2>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Status</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for s in workbenchFeatures.weStatusScale %}
    <tr><td><strong>{{ s.label }}</strong></td><td>{{ s.test }}</td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h2>The feature surface</h2>
{% for g in workbenchFeatures.featureGroups %}
<h3>{{ g.label }}</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Ubiquity</th><th>WE status</th><th>Maps to</th><th>What a WE-native version needs</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for f in workbenchFeatures.features %}{% if f.group == g.id %}
    <tr>
      <td><strong>{{ f.label }}</strong></td>
      <td>{{ f.ubiquity }}</td>
      <td>{{ f.weStatus }}</td>
      <td>{{ f.weStandards | join(", ") }}</td>
      <td>{{ f.weNativeNeed }}</td>
    </tr>
    {% endif %}{% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
{% endfor %}

<h2>Tool coverage per feature</h2>
<p>The cross-tab — which landscape tools ship each capability (tool ids from the workbench-tools registry).</p>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Tools that ship it</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for f in workbenchFeatures.features %}
    <tr><td><strong>{{ f.label }}</strong></td><td>{{ f.tools | join(", ") }}</td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h2>Re-running this sweep</h2>
<p>
  Keyed by stable feature <code>id</code> and tool <code>id</code> so a re-run produces a clean diff. To
  refresh: re-walk each tool for the feature set, add any new capability axis that clears into the landscape,
  re-check the <code>weStatus</code> mapping against the current WE registry, and bump <code>lastSwept</code>.
</p>
